
In recent years, UPI has made digital payments fast and convenient, but it has also increased the risk of online fraud. One such case involved a college student named Rahul. He received a call from a person claiming to be a bank representative. The caller said that Rahul’s bank account would be blocked if he did not complete a quick verification process.

Trusting the caller, Rahul followed the instructions and was asked to open his UPI app and enter a request sent to him. He believed it was for verification, but in reality, it was a “collect request” to transfer money. Without realizing it, he approved the request, and ₹10,000 was deducted from his account.

After noticing the transaction, Rahul immediately contacted his bank and reported the fraud. Although the bank tried to help, the money could not be fully recovered. This incident taught him the importance of being cautious while handling online payments.

This case highlights that fraudsters often use fear and urgency to trick people. Users should never share personal details, OTPs, or approve unknown payment requests. It is important to verify the source and stay alert. Digital awareness and careful usage can help prevent such frauds and ensure safe online transactions.
